Claims CLAIMS: 1. A submodule for a modular multilevel voltage sourced converter comprising: two terminals for electrically connecting the submodule within the modular multilevel voltage sourced converter and defining a submodule voltage; an energy storage device adapted to provide a substantially constant voltage value; a first pairing of antiparallel-connected unidirectional-current conducting electronic components electrically connected in series with the energy storage device to form a first branch of the submodule which is electrically connected between the terminals and along which current can flow between the terminals such that the submodule voltage is substantially equal to the substantially constant voltage value of the energy storage device; the first pairing of electronic components including a first power electronic switch which is configured to conduct current when a control signal is applied thereto, the first power electronic switch being oriented to conduct current in a first direction generally from a first one of the terminals towards a second one of the terminals; a second pairing of antiparallel-connected unidirectional-current conducting electronic components electrically connected between the terminals in parallel with the first branch so as to form a second branch of the submodule along which current can flow between the terminals such that the submodule voltage is substantially zero; the second pairing of electronic components including a second power electronic switch which is configured to conduct current when a control signal is applied thereto, the second power electronic switch being oriented to conduct current in a second direction generally from the second terminal towards the first terminal, so as to be opposite to the first direction; the second pairing of electronic components including a third power electronic switch which is configured to conduct current when a control signal is applied thereto and to cease to conduct the current in an absence of said control signal once the current passing through the third electronic switch substantially falls to zero after said control signal has been removed, the third power electronic switch being oriented to conduct current in the first direction generally from the first terminal towards the second terminal and being configured to withstand voltage up to a prescribed voltage value of a first polarity corresponding to the current-conducting direction and a second opposite polarity thereto; and a control arrangement configured for sending the control signals to the power electronic switches to operate the submodule in a power conversion condition having an inserted state in which the first pairing of electronic components is activated to conduct the current so that the submodule voltage is equal to the substantially constant voltage value of the energy storage device and a bypassed state in which the second pairing of electronic components is activated to conduct the current so that the submodule voltage is substantially zero; 

 the control arrangement being configured to detect a direction of current flow through the submodule and to be responsive to detection of a DC fault to operate the submodule in a DC fault suppression condition in which: if the current conducted by the submodule is flowing into the second terminal and out of the first terminal, the control signals to the first, second and third power electronic switches are substantially simultaneously blocked; if the current conducted by the submodule Is flowing into the first terminal and out of the second terminal and the submodule was operating in the bypassed state prior to the detection of the DC fault, the control signals to the first, second and third power electronic switches are substantially simultaneously blocked; and if the current conducted by the submodule is flowing into the first terminal and out of the second terminal and the submodule was operating in the inserted state prior to the detection of the DC fault, (i) the control signals to the first and second power electronic switches are substantially simultaneously blocked and, substantially simultaneously therewith, the control signal to the third power electronic switch is applied such that the current conducted by the first power electronic switch prior to the detection of the DC fault can be transferred to the third power electronic switch so as to continue to flow through the submodule without being interrupted; and (ii) once a prescribed time has elapsed after sending the control signal to the third power electronic switch such that the current through the submodule is flowing through the third power electronic switch, the control signal to the third power electronic switch is blocked. 2. The submodule of claim 1 wherein the third power electronic switch is a thyristor. 3. The submodule of claim 1 or 2 wherein there is provided a diode electrically connected in series with second power electronic switch such that the diode in series therewith is antiparallel-connected to the third power electronic switch, and the second power electronic switch is configured to withstand up to a prescribed voltage value only of a first polarity corresponding to the current-conducting direction but not an opposite polarity thereto. 4. The submodule of any one of claims 1 to 3 wherein, in the power conversion condition, the control arrangement is configured to apply the control signal to the third power electronic switch when current is flowing into the first terminal and out of the second terminal in the bypassed state. 5. The submodule of any one of claims 1 to 4 wherein the prescribed time from the sending of the control signal to the third power electronic switch to the blocking thereof is about 1 microsecond to about 1 millisecond. 6. A method of suppressing a DC fault in an AC-DC power conversion system including a modular multilevel voltage sourced converter, comprising: 

 providing the modular multilevel voltage sourced converter having at least one arm each interconnecting a phase of an AC power system to a DC power system, each of the arms including a plurality of submodules, each submodule comprising: two terminals for electrically connecting the submodule within the modular multilevel voltage sourced converter and defining a submodule voltage; an energy storage device adapted to provide a substantially constant voltage value; a first bi-directional switch assembly configured to conduct current in two directions electrically connected in series with the energy storage device to form a first branch of the submodule along which current can flow between the terminals such that the submodule voltage is substantially equal to the substantially constant voltage value of the energy storage device, the first bi-directional switch assembly being configured to conduct current in at least one of the two directions when a control signal is applied thereto; a second bi-directional switch assembly configured to conduct current in two direction electrically connected in parallel with the first branch to form a second branch of the submodule along which current can flow between the terminals such that the submodule voltage is substantially zero, the second bi-directional switch assembly being configured to conduct current in each of the two directions when a control signal is applied thereto; upon detection of the DC fault, operating each one of the submodules of a common one of the at least one arm so as not to conduct current therethrough thus forming an open circuit for blocking a fault current generated by the DC fault. 7. The method of claim 6 wherein each submodule is the submodule of any one of claims 1 to 5.
